1
00:01:40,309 --> 00:01:42,017
Take her off!

2
00:01:51,236 --> 00:01:52,861
Giddap!

3
00:02:06,251 --> 00:02:07,662
Somebody help me!

4
00:02:11,798 --> 00:02:13,874
Help me!

5
00:03:07,980 --> 00:03:09,522
Tom!

6
00:03:15,612 --> 00:03:16,941
Cut!

7
00:03:18,156 --> 00:03:20,908
- I said cut.
- That was great.

8
00:03:21,159 --> 00:03:23,781
Okay, that's lunch. Half an hour.

9
00:03:40,012 --> 00:03:41,839
- Hi, Tom.
- Alfie.

10
00:03:42,055 --> 00:03:44,262
- Hello, Tom.
- Miss Victoria.

11
00:03:44,516 --> 00:03:47,885
- You look mighty pretty today.
- Thanks. So do you.

12
00:03:48,103 --> 00:03:50,938
Let's go for a walk, Tom.

13
00:03:52,941 --> 00:03:54,981
Randy, bring a couple chairs.

14
00:03:55,235 --> 00:03:57,477
The film's looking very good.

15
00:03:57,696 --> 00:04:01,030
Afraid we may have
another big hit on our hands.

16
00:04:01,241 --> 00:04:04,444
- You came here to tell me that?
- No.

17
00:04:04,661 --> 00:04:08,706
- How are you, Mr. Alperin?
- I didn't think so.

18
00:04:14,796 --> 00:04:18,580
I just bought a sensational
script called Lawman.

19
00:04:18,842 --> 00:04:22,294
About a famous frontier marshal,
Wyatt Earp.

20
00:04:22,513 --> 00:04:24,754
Yeah, I heard of him.

21
00:04:25,891 --> 00:04:29,936
"Alperin Films presents Tom Mix,
Hollywood's cowboy...

22
00:04:30,187 --> 00:04:33,971
...starring as Wyatt Earp,
the West's famous lawman."

23
00:04:34,233 --> 00:04:38,645
- I'll get Earp as technical advisor.
- Now hold on!

24
00:04:40,030 --> 00:04:45,617
I didn't become numero uno at the
box office by playing other people.

25
00:04:48,580 --> 00:04:54,204
Tom, this is a very
important project to me.

26
00:04:54,586 --> 00:04:57,256
Fox and Chaplin are gambling on sound.

27
00:04:57,506 --> 00:05:01,420
I'm betting my bankroll
on you in Lawman.

28
00:05:05,347 --> 00:05:07,672
What if I don't agree?

29
00:05:09,476 --> 00:05:14,185
Fact is, I'll be very unappy.

30
00:05:15,023 --> 00:05:18,190
And you'll have to sit out
your contract.

31
00:05:18,443 --> 00:05:23,271
Whers it up? March '33?
That's four years.

32
00:05:24,116 --> 00:05:27,615
What are we saying?
You havert read the script yet.

33
00:05:27,828 --> 00:05:30,995
I may be wrong,
but I'm sure you'll love it.

34
00:05:37,129 --> 00:05:41,173
Well, I'll read it.
I'll let you know in the morning.

35
00:05:41,425 --> 00:05:44,046
Fine.
I wanna start shooting next month.

36
00:05:44,261 --> 00:05:47,381
I still have to talk
to the famous marshal.

37
00:05:47,598 --> 00:05:50,349
All right, let's get back to work.

38
00:05:50,767 --> 00:05:55,762
It should be educational,
working with a real gunfighter.

39
00:05:56,023 --> 00:05:59,107
Maybe he'll give you some pointers.

40
00:05:59,359 --> 00:06:02,645
Yeah, I bet he will.

41
00:06:06,533 --> 00:06:09,618
You've got the wrong end
of the horse.

42
00:06:09,870 --> 00:06:12,028
Depends on how you look at it.

43
00:06:12,456 --> 00:06:17,996
If you was Tony Jr. Here, you'd think
you got the wrong end of Tom Mix.

44
00:06:29,640 --> 00:06:31,383
Here comes Alfie.

45
00:06:32,851 --> 00:06:35,425
- Bye, Alfie.
- Bye.

46
00:06:35,854 --> 00:06:39,140
- Did he say yes?
- No, but he will.

47
00:08:09,489 --> 00:08:10,770
Where's he going?

48
00:08:10,991 --> 00:08:15,617
- It's been a pleasure, Mr. Earp.
- Feeling's mutual, George.

49
00:08:17,706 --> 00:08:21,953
- Mr. Wyatt Earp?
- That's right. Tom Mix, isn't it?

50
00:08:22,878 --> 00:08:24,076
That's right.

51
00:08:24,713 --> 00:08:27,286
Can I give you a lift into town?

52
00:08:27,508 --> 00:08:28,706
On your horse?

53
00:08:28,926 --> 00:08:32,591
No, Tony Jr. Ain't got
no license plates.

54
00:08:32,846 --> 00:08:36,511
I'm afraid you'll have to ride
in the Duesenberg.

55
00:08:38,560 --> 00:08:41,431
There's a press conference at 2:00.

56
00:08:41,688 --> 00:08:48,106
At 3:30, you meet with Mr. Alperin.
At 4, we have a photo session.

57
00:08:48,320 --> 00:08:52,816
Will he have enough time to get
to the radio station by 5:30?

58
00:08:53,033 --> 00:08:58,158
If we finish the photos by 4:45.
Do you have clothes that look Western?

59
00:08:58,372 --> 00:09:00,115
We'll get something in wardrobe.

60
00:09:00,374 --> 00:09:04,454
You look a like a Texas oil man
instead of a sheriff.

61
00:09:04,670 --> 00:09:08,121
- A marshal.
- Marshal. What's the difference?

62
00:09:11,218 --> 00:09:13,175
Hey, here they come!

63
00:09:15,389 --> 00:09:17,595
Would you ever consider acting?

64
00:09:17,808 --> 00:09:20,975
Excuse me.
I'm not gonna like staying here.

65
00:09:21,228 --> 00:09:25,641
Then let's find you a place
where you will like staying.

66
00:09:26,650 --> 00:09:31,276
Will Alperin be disappointed
if I don't show up for those things?

67
00:09:31,530 --> 00:09:33,439
Yeah. That worry you?

68
00:09:33,699 --> 00:09:36,735
I hired on as an advisor,
not a celebrity.

69
00:09:37,244 --> 00:09:39,071
Well, that's it.

70
00:09:39,288 --> 00:09:43,036
I lived here before I got famous.
Quiet. Private.

71
00:09:43,292 --> 00:09:47,539
- Washed my socks in the sink.
- Think you can get me in?

72
00:09:47,796 --> 00:09:51,794
Sure, I own it.
Mi casa es su casa.

73
00:09:52,009 --> 00:09:55,793
- You learn Spanish in Cuba?
- You knew I was in Cuba?

74
00:09:56,054 --> 00:09:59,091
I read about it in the Sunday paper.

75
00:09:59,308 --> 00:10:02,759
- Lf it's in print, it's gotta be true.
- Absolutely.

76
00:10:03,020 --> 00:10:07,765
In the Chicago Tribune
they said you were in the Boer War.

77
00:10:08,025 --> 00:10:12,983
- Any photos?
- No, just sketches and engravings.

78
00:10:13,197 --> 00:10:16,862
Engravings? Isn't that how
counterfeiters make funny money?

79
00:10:18,076 --> 00:10:20,199
Cue the Earps.

80
00:10:50,609 --> 00:10:53,147
- Dialogue!
- You're under arrest.

81
00:11:03,539 --> 00:11:05,780
Don't kill me!
I ain't shooting!

82
00:11:05,999 --> 00:11:09,748
The fight's commenced.
Get to fighting or get out.

83
00:11:31,275 --> 00:11:33,563
Dialogue, Billy.

84
00:11:33,777 --> 00:11:39,116
God, forgive me for all
the bad things I've done.

85
00:11:41,368 --> 00:11:42,993
Cut!

86
00:11:43,328 --> 00:11:48,405
- We'll do the close- ups after lunch.
- All right, that's lunch.

87
00:11:49,459 --> 00:11:51,701
- Was it okay?
- Okay for me.

88
00:11:51,962 --> 00:11:55,580
- Was that really just like it?
- Just like it.

89
00:11:56,300 --> 00:11:59,004
I want to get Tom's close- ups first.

90
00:12:01,972 --> 00:12:04,843
Tom, that was interesting.

91
00:12:05,309 --> 00:12:09,009
- Suggestions?
- No. You handle a six-gun pretty good.

92
00:12:09,271 --> 00:12:12,557
- Praise from Caesar.
- Can you hit anything?

93
00:12:12,774 --> 00:12:17,187
You gotta hit what you shoot at.
I just gotta look good.

94
00:12:18,030 --> 00:12:20,485
Was that really the way it was?

95
00:12:20,741 --> 00:12:24,240
- Absolutely. Give or take a lie or two.
- Mr. Earp.

96
00:12:24,494 --> 00:12:26,783
Good morning, Miss Shoemaker.

97
00:12:27,039 --> 00:12:29,245
- Can I talk to you?
- Sure.

98
00:12:29,458 --> 00:12:31,285
Honey, I'm gonna propose.

99
00:12:31,585 --> 00:12:34,539
If you don't do publicity,
I'll lose my job.

100
00:12:35,172 --> 00:12:40,546
I don't want that to happen.
I'll work it out with Mr. Alperin.

101
00:12:40,802 --> 00:12:45,548
I know Alfie. He won't talk
until he gets his pound of flesh.

102
00:12:45,766 --> 00:12:48,886
Do you mind if I try anyway?

103
00:12:49,144 --> 00:12:54,351
- Okay, Mr. Earp.
- Would you mind making that Wyatt?

104
00:12:55,067 --> 00:12:57,059
Sure, if you make it Nancy.

105
00:12:57,653 --> 00:13:00,440
You warm an old mars heart, Nancy.

106
00:13:00,697 --> 00:13:05,940
Shame on you, Wyatt, trying to pull
that old man stuff on me.

107
00:13:08,497 --> 00:13:11,249
Mr. Earp?
Chief Dibner wants to see you.

108
00:13:11,500 --> 00:13:14,335
- Who?
- Chief of security. I'll take you.

109
00:13:14,586 --> 00:13:17,457
No need.
Just point me in the direction.

110
00:13:17,714 --> 00:13:21,214
Go down Main Street.
Last bungalow on the left.

111
00:13:21,468 --> 00:13:24,754
- Sounds easy. Thanks, officer.
- You're welcome.

112
00:13:25,013 --> 00:13:26,211
Hey, Wyatt.

113
00:13:26,473 --> 00:13:29,510
- Where you headed?
- Chief Dibner wants me.

114
00:13:29,726 --> 00:13:32,300
Hold on a minute.

115
00:13:36,483 --> 00:13:38,310
- Make him come to you.
- Why?

116
00:13:38,527 --> 00:13:41,397
Because he's a dangerous
son of a bitch.

117
00:13:41,655 --> 00:13:45,569
You know what they say about
bearding a lion in his den.

118
00:13:45,784 --> 00:13:50,612
Sometimes the same thing applies
to dangerous sons of bitches.

119
00:13:50,873 --> 00:13:53,957
You could've made a hell of an actor.

120
00:13:54,168 --> 00:13:57,168
Marshalling and acting
arert too far apart.

121
00:13:57,421 --> 00:14:02,711
One time, I wasrt packing my six-gun,
and Doc Holliday was drunk.

122
00:14:02,968 --> 00:14:06,551
He was roaring he was gonna
shoot my earlobes off.

123
00:14:06,805 --> 00:14:08,928
I went for a hideout gun.

124
00:14:09,183 --> 00:14:11,638
Luckily, he thought I had one.

125
00:14:11,894 --> 00:14:15,179
- Is that the truth?
- Oh, every word.

126
00:14:15,397 --> 00:14:17,853
Give or take a lie or two.

127
00:14:18,192 --> 00:14:20,101
Watch yourself, amigo.

128
00:14:51,558 --> 00:14:55,259
It's just a Western.
Some Indians die, big deal.

129
00:14:55,521 --> 00:14:58,012
- Watch your step.
- Michael, please!

130
00:14:58,273 --> 00:14:59,388
Hold on.

131
00:14:59,608 --> 00:15:03,771
Excuse me, but you're in the way
of some very dedicated drinking.

132
00:15:04,029 --> 00:15:05,689
Well, I'm sorry.

133
00:15:05,948 --> 00:15:08,355
Hey! What picture are you in?

134
00:15:08,575 --> 00:15:10,153
I'm not.

135
00:15:11,245 --> 00:15:14,448
- Well, then who are you?
- Name's Earp.

136
00:15:14,665 --> 00:15:15,993
Wyatt Earp?

137
00:15:16,667 --> 00:15:20,499
Well, I'm Billy the Kid,
and she's Calamity Jane.

138
00:15:21,255 --> 00:15:26,497
Mary Jane Canary was a dear woman,
but she looked like an unmade bed.

139
00:15:26,760 --> 00:15:31,552
- This young lady's much too pretty.
- Thank you, Mr. Earp.

140
00:15:33,392 --> 00:15:35,515
Mr. Earp is here.

141
00:15:40,232 --> 00:15:42,557
I'm Marvin Dibner.

142
00:15:42,985 --> 00:15:45,310
Well, have a seat.

143
00:15:54,079 --> 00:15:59,915
Apparently, Mrs. Alperin knows
you're here in Hollywood.

144
00:16:01,420 --> 00:16:06,497
Mrs. Alperin would like you
to pay a call on her as a favour.

145
00:16:07,634 --> 00:16:10,090
You know who she is?

146
00:16:11,263 --> 00:16:13,754
Did you ever meet her?

147
00:16:15,726 --> 00:16:20,020
- You don't say much, do you, Wyatt?
- No, I don't.

148
00:16:20,272 --> 00:16:23,771
Also, it's Mr. Earp.
Or Marshal, or even Earp.

149
00:16:24,026 --> 00:16:27,940
Not Wyatt until I tell you.
And while I think of it...

150
00:16:28,197 --> 00:16:30,770
...don't ever question me again.

151
00:16:31,033 --> 00:16:33,524
Just trying to be friendly.

152
00:16:33,744 --> 00:16:36,579
You're trying to stay
ahead of the game.

153
00:16:36,788 --> 00:16:40,917
Your boss's wife wants to talk to me,
you want to know why.

154
00:16:41,126 --> 00:16:43,747
Probably your boss does too.

155
00:16:49,551 --> 00:16:54,462
My job is to get curious about
anything involving Mrs. Alperin.

156
00:16:54,681 --> 00:16:58,346
- You know what she wants?
- Why not ask Mrs. Alperin?

157
00:16:58,560 --> 00:17:00,469
What's bothering you?

158
00:17:00,687 --> 00:17:04,352
Your bad manners and the fact
you don't hear too good.

159
00:17:04,608 --> 00:17:08,558
I told you not to try questioning me.

160
00:17:08,862 --> 00:17:11,187
And I meant it.

161
00:17:37,099 --> 00:17:39,056
- Thank you.
- Thanks, Mr. Earp.

162
00:17:39,309 --> 00:17:42,310
- Can I help you?
- With what?

163
00:17:46,400 --> 00:17:51,774
First off, don't ever crowd anybody
unless you got a first-class reason.

164
00:17:53,949 --> 00:17:56,570
Did you do a lot of time, boy?

165
00:17:58,161 --> 00:18:00,201
- Where?
- Folsom.

166
00:18:00,455 --> 00:18:02,247
For what?

167
00:18:03,292 --> 00:18:05,747
Armed robbery.

168
00:18:06,086 --> 00:18:09,455
Make a move, it'll be
the mistake of your life.

169
00:18:09,715 --> 00:18:12,669
- Am I clear?
- Oh, yeah.

170
00:18:17,848 --> 00:18:22,095
- Yes, sir?
- Marshal Earp to see Mrs. Alperin.

171
00:18:22,853 --> 00:18:24,929
If you'll follow me.

172
00:18:30,068 --> 00:18:33,852
I'll inform Mrs. Alperin
that you're here.

173
00:18:44,875 --> 00:18:47,366
Not much like Denver.

174
00:18:49,463 --> 00:18:52,796
Mr. Earp, thank you for coming.

175
00:18:55,260 --> 00:18:59,472
- I've hoped to see you again.
- I wanted to hear from you.

176
00:18:59,723 --> 00:19:04,432
It wouldn't have been fitting.
I didn't think you'd remember.

177
00:19:04,645 --> 00:19:06,768
You've never been forgotten.

178
00:19:07,022 --> 00:19:10,771
You are just as I remember.
Perhaps taller.

179
00:19:10,984 --> 00:19:14,852
- Is it possible that you grew?
- Not likely.

180
00:19:15,113 --> 00:19:18,399
Then there can only be
one explanation.

181
00:19:18,617 --> 00:19:20,693
I was wearing high heels.

182
00:19:20,953 --> 00:19:25,282
You were. Soft, gray kid
high-button shoes.

183
00:19:25,874 --> 00:19:29,124
- How could you remember?
- I undid them.

184
00:19:29,920 --> 00:19:33,170
- The buttons were yellow ivory.
- Whalebone.

185
00:19:37,970 --> 00:19:40,924
That night in Denver,
you said...

186
00:19:41,181 --> 00:19:44,930
That if you were ever in trouble,
I'd come.

187
00:19:47,187 --> 00:19:50,770
Let's go outside where we won't
be interrupted.

188
00:20:05,539 --> 00:20:10,533
Alfie told me you were here,
and everyone else is afraid.

189
00:20:10,794 --> 00:20:14,626
- Afraid?
- Of each other. Of...

190
00:20:14,882 --> 00:20:16,506
Of your husband?

191
00:20:16,800 --> 00:20:18,592
Yes, I suppose so.

192
00:20:18,844 --> 00:20:22,842
They're afraid Alfie might not
want me helped.

193
00:20:23,098 --> 00:20:24,842
With your son?

194
00:20:25,475 --> 00:20:28,049
I met him today at the studio.

195
00:20:28,312 --> 00:20:31,266
- Was he...?
- Drinking? Yes.

196
00:20:38,655 --> 00:20:44,326
I received a letter from a woman
I used to know named Candace Girard.

197
00:20:44,578 --> 00:20:49,204
She runs a place
called the Candy Store.

198
00:20:49,458 --> 00:20:55,163
She says Michael hurt one of her girls
and I suggests I buy her off.

199
00:20:55,380 --> 00:20:59,758
- What was the girl's name?
- Rhonda Lopez. Please see her.

200
00:21:00,010 --> 00:21:03,011
I've no one to turn to.
I'll pay anything.

201
00:21:03,263 --> 00:21:08,850
I'm not for hire. I'll do it
for the way you held the roses.

202
00:21:15,234 --> 00:21:20,109
Christina Alperirs a very lovely lady
who married the wrong man.

203
00:21:20,364 --> 00:21:23,318
Easy to understand.
When she met Alfie...

204
00:21:23,534 --> 00:21:26,155
...he didn't want
to take over the world.

205
00:21:26,411 --> 00:21:32,746
He was still "The Happy Hobo"
that people laughed at and loved.

206
00:21:33,877 --> 00:21:38,835
I'm here to tell you, Wyatt,
when he wanted to be...

207
00:21:39,842 --> 00:21:44,420
...he could be the most charming,
considerate...

208
00:21:44,680 --> 00:21:47,349
...giving, funny man.

209
00:21:48,475 --> 00:21:51,262
Especially when he wanted something.

210
00:21:51,687 --> 00:21:54,688
He sure did want Christina.

211
00:21:57,609 --> 00:21:59,816
Arert you hot?

212
00:22:01,405 --> 00:22:02,567
It's open.

213
00:22:04,449 --> 00:22:08,827
- The press awaits.
- Better get her done, pardner.

214
00:22:12,583 --> 00:22:17,957
I explained that you have pressing
engagements and must be done by 6:30.

215
00:22:18,213 --> 00:22:20,669
- How did you know that?
- I didn't.

216
00:22:20,883 --> 00:22:23,374
Tom's taking me on a tour.

217
00:22:23,844 --> 00:22:29,004
Starting with Graumars Chinese
and ending up at the Candy Store.

218
00:22:50,704 --> 00:22:52,993
- Good evening, Mr. Mix.
- Cheryl.

219
00:22:53,207 --> 00:22:56,540
Allow me to introduce Mr. Wyatt Earp.

220
00:22:56,793 --> 00:23:00,293
- The real Wyatt Earp?
- Yes, I'm not dead yet.

221
00:23:00,547 --> 00:23:01,745
I can see that.

222
00:23:02,007 --> 00:23:06,420
Promise not to close us down
like the saloons in Tombstone.

223
00:23:06,678 --> 00:23:11,139
- I never closed a saloon in my life.
- Good.

224
00:23:15,020 --> 00:23:17,392
- We know what Tom drinks.
- I'll have...

225
00:23:17,648 --> 00:23:21,182
No, let me guess.
A Waterfill and Frazier...

226
00:23:21,443 --> 00:23:25,108
...and a cold Dos Equis to chase.

227
00:23:25,322 --> 00:23:26,401
Close enough.

228
00:23:26,823 --> 00:23:32,114
- How long do you plan to be in town?
- As long as I find it interesting.

229
00:23:32,371 --> 00:23:37,246
- We'll do what we can to keep you.
- I think that'd be nice.

230
00:23:37,459 --> 00:23:39,867
- Cheryl.
- Miss Alperin.

231
00:23:40,546 --> 00:23:44,128
Victoria Alperin,
Alfie's kid sister, and...

232
00:23:44,383 --> 00:23:46,459
Dutch Kieffer.

233
00:23:46,969 --> 00:23:50,966
I'm surprised a marshal
knows the Chicago underworld.

234
00:23:51,223 --> 00:23:54,508
East or West, a crook is a crook.

235
00:23:55,602 --> 00:24:00,395
Did Tom tell you that our ladies
all look like famous movie stars?

236
00:24:00,858 --> 00:24:03,693
Greta? This is Mr. Wyatt Earp.

237
00:24:03,944 --> 00:24:08,570
- It's a pleasure, Mr. Earp.
- My pleasure, Ms. Garbo.

238
00:24:14,079 --> 00:24:15,538
Amazing resemblance.

239
00:24:15,914 --> 00:24:20,375
Yes, and besides Greta,
we have Janet Gaynor, Pola Negri...

240
00:24:20,669 --> 00:24:22,709
...and the Gish sisters.

241
00:24:22,963 --> 00:24:25,419
I forget you're here on business.

242
00:24:25,674 --> 00:24:30,217
Mrs. Alperin wanted me to talk
to Candace Girard.

243
00:24:31,180 --> 00:24:34,880
I see. About the girl
that Michael beat up?

244
00:24:35,142 --> 00:24:36,802
Yes.

245
00:24:37,019 --> 00:24:39,973
You'll find Candace
in the guest cottage.

246
00:24:40,189 --> 00:24:44,056
That's where she lives
and sometimes entertains.

247
00:24:44,318 --> 00:24:47,852
Use the back door.
Tom knows the way.

248
00:24:52,618 --> 00:24:55,784
Will you be here when I get back?

249
00:24:57,080 --> 00:24:59,654
Depends on when you get back.

250
00:24:59,917 --> 00:25:02,158
How you doing, pal?

251
00:25:03,086 --> 00:25:05,791
Hiya, big boy.

252
00:25:16,808 --> 00:25:18,386
Honeysuckle.

253
00:25:19,353 --> 00:25:24,394
- You arert what I expected you to be.
- What exactly did you expect?

254
00:25:24,650 --> 00:25:28,149
I don't know, exactly.
A little less civilized.

255
00:25:28,362 --> 00:25:32,525
You're not exactly what
I expected you to be, either.

256
00:25:32,783 --> 00:25:35,700
What exactly did you expect I'd be?

257
00:25:35,953 --> 00:25:38,076
Taller, maybe.

258
00:25:39,164 --> 00:25:42,829
Candy! It's Tom Mix, honey.

259
00:25:44,628 --> 00:25:46,039
Candy!

260
00:25:58,141 --> 00:26:00,181
- Cadillac Eight.
- Recognize it?

261
00:26:00,435 --> 00:26:02,179
No.

262
00:26:03,188 --> 00:26:05,596
I got a lousy feeling about this.

263
00:26:05,858 --> 00:26:09,108
Yeah, I got the same lousy feeling.

264
00:26:11,989 --> 00:26:13,447
Candy!

265
00:26:14,908 --> 00:26:16,367
Candy?

266
00:26:21,290 --> 00:26:23,329
Oh, shit.

267
00:26:45,355 --> 00:26:48,475
- Michael Alperin.
- Yeah, we met. Get the car.

268
00:26:51,570 --> 00:26:54,903
Candy! Open up, it's important.

269
00:26:56,366 --> 00:26:58,276
- It's a raid.
- Where's the car?

270
00:26:58,535 --> 00:27:00,943
- Killed her!
- What's going on?

271
00:27:01,163 --> 00:27:03,654
- What happened?
- Don't go in there!

272
00:27:04,082 --> 00:27:07,914
- No! No!
- Cheryl, come on! Cheryl!

273
00:27:11,006 --> 00:27:14,422
Tom! Get your hat and close this door!

274
00:27:14,635 --> 00:27:17,173
- Cheryl! Shut up!
- No!

275
00:27:18,180 --> 00:27:20,552
Cheryl! Listen to me!

276
00:27:20,766 --> 00:27:22,758
Listen to me! Listen!

277
00:27:25,395 --> 00:27:28,396
Get down! Get down!

278
00:27:30,776 --> 00:27:35,651
Pull yourself together.
Go in there and keep your mouth shut.

279
00:27:39,868 --> 00:27:41,861
Come on, Tom!

280
00:27:47,543 --> 00:27:50,294
- I didn't know you could drive.
- I can't.

281
00:27:53,131 --> 00:27:54,923
Hey, look out!

282
00:28:11,817 --> 00:28:13,809
Close that door, honey.

283
00:28:17,322 --> 00:28:19,778
- Get him undressed.
- Will you tell...?

284
00:28:19,992 --> 00:28:21,901
Candy Girard was murdered.

285
00:28:22,160 --> 00:28:26,110
They're looking for Michael.
We gotta keep him here.

286
00:28:26,373 --> 00:28:28,247
- He did it?
- I don't think so.

287
00:28:28,500 --> 00:28:30,208
- I killed her.
- He disagrees.

288
00:28:30,460 --> 00:28:31,575
He's drugged.

289
00:28:31,837 --> 00:28:36,048
- You mean drunk.
- That too. He's gonna be sick again.

290
00:28:36,258 --> 00:28:37,717
Towels!

291
00:28:37,926 --> 00:28:40,049
- You sure about her?
- Real sure.

292
00:28:40,304 --> 00:28:43,720
- That's sure enough for me.
- Honey, come on.

293
00:28:44,016 --> 00:28:45,558
Wait, wait.

294
00:28:48,770 --> 00:28:53,895
- We gotta go. Can you handle this?
- Sure, I'll just pretend he's my ex.

295
00:28:54,151 --> 00:28:58,860
- It's gonna be a couple of days.
- I'll manage. I'll call in sick.

296
00:28:59,114 --> 00:29:01,819
I'll call you as soon as I get home.

297
00:29:02,910 --> 00:29:05,317
Tom, come on.

298
00:29:06,538 --> 00:29:11,533
- What if he decides to leave?
- Where is he going without his pants?

299
00:29:16,882 --> 00:29:18,791
I killed her.

300
00:29:19,468 --> 00:29:22,173
God, I hope you're lying.

301
00:29:54,294 --> 00:29:55,872
Wyatt.

302
00:30:20,362 --> 00:30:22,271
I'm okay.

303
00:30:23,323 --> 00:30:25,280
I'm all right.

304
00:30:30,372 --> 00:30:32,780
Will you sleep with me?

305
00:30:33,709 --> 00:30:36,710
I'm old enough to be your father.

306
00:30:37,212 --> 00:30:42,918
You're old enough to be my grandfather.
Now answer the question.

307
00:30:43,719 --> 00:30:45,758
Yes.

308
00:30:48,182 --> 00:30:51,432
I just need to be held.

309
00:30:55,689 --> 00:30:59,983
At one time or another, we all do.

310
00:31:08,535 --> 00:31:12,533
- Why did you tell Cheryl where I was?
- She asked me.

311
00:31:12,789 --> 00:31:15,459
I figured if she asked,
you'd tell her.

312
00:31:15,709 --> 00:31:17,037
- Was I wrong?
- Nope.

313
00:31:17,252 --> 00:31:18,711
Grand girl.

314
00:31:18,921 --> 00:31:23,915
A grand 26-year-old girl.
Could've done myself permanent injury.

315
00:31:25,969 --> 00:31:28,840
- How many men you killed?
- How many cars you got?

316
00:31:29,014 --> 00:31:32,300
- About 16.
- You got more cars.

317
00:31:32,976 --> 00:31:34,601
Mr. Mix!

318
00:31:38,232 --> 00:31:42,810
Captain Dibner wants you and Mr. Earp
to report to his office.

319
00:31:47,574 --> 00:31:49,899
Mr. Mix and Mr. Earp.

320
00:31:56,875 --> 00:32:01,169
Wyatt Earp, Captain Blackwon'th, P.D.
Tom, you know him.

321
00:32:02,756 --> 00:32:04,630
Have a seat.

322
00:32:11,098 --> 00:32:14,514
You boys were at the Candy Store
last night.

323
00:32:15,269 --> 00:32:18,472
- Was we?
- Guess we was.

324
00:32:19,606 --> 00:32:23,189
Candace Girard was killed
shortly before you left.

325
00:32:23,986 --> 00:32:26,773
- Did you know that, Wyatt?
- Yeah.

326
00:32:27,698 --> 00:32:31,114
- Dib, you got a drink?
- Yes, sir.

327
00:32:36,582 --> 00:32:38,491
I'm a tequila man.

328
00:32:38,876 --> 00:32:40,952
Waterfill and Frazier.

329
00:32:44,631 --> 00:32:48,380
You saw a girl. Cheryl.

330
00:32:49,094 --> 00:32:52,629
Gotta hand it to you.
You sure are up on things.

331
00:32:53,265 --> 00:32:56,764
We need to talk to her.
She was...

332
00:32:57,186 --> 00:32:59,427
...close with Candy.

333
00:33:00,689 --> 00:33:02,598
Real close.

334
00:33:07,988 --> 00:33:10,740
Maybe you'd talk at headquarters.

335
00:33:11,158 --> 00:33:15,452
So far, you've been telling us things.
Ask questions, you'll get answers.

336
00:33:15,787 --> 00:33:18,539
What do you know about Candy's murder?

337
00:33:18,749 --> 00:33:20,492
Very little.

338
00:33:20,751 --> 00:33:22,909
Practically nothing.

339
00:33:23,170 --> 00:33:25,708
No idea who killed her?

340
00:33:26,507 --> 00:33:30,919
- Could be the man in the black Cadillac.
- What black Cadillac?

341
00:33:31,136 --> 00:33:34,470
The one that drove out of the alley.

342
00:33:34,723 --> 00:33:38,388
- Licence number.
- I forget.

343
00:33:39,102 --> 00:33:42,637
Yeah, I forget too.

344
00:33:43,273 --> 00:33:47,603
Well, if I was you,
I'd damn well try to remember.

345
00:33:47,819 --> 00:33:52,031
You'd have trouble remembering
when you get pushed hard.

346
00:33:52,282 --> 00:33:57,028
Let me give you an example.
Why did you raid the Candy Store?

347
00:33:57,287 --> 00:34:00,822
It was engaged in the practice
of prostitution.

348
00:34:01,041 --> 00:34:03,497
That's illegal here.

349
00:34:03,752 --> 00:34:05,033
Come on, captain.

350
00:34:05,254 --> 00:34:08,872
Candy's been around a long time.
It's a gold mine.

351
00:34:09,132 --> 00:34:13,462
To stay open, she had to be
paying someone a lot of juice.

352
00:34:13,720 --> 00:34:17,765
I don't know. That's not
my department, that's vice.

353
00:34:17,975 --> 00:34:22,637
Well, there you go.
That's the way it is in the big city.

354
00:34:22,855 --> 00:34:28,062
Everybody's in another department.
All nice and legal.

355
00:34:28,318 --> 00:34:32,945
Tell me, captain. With all those
different departments...

356
00:34:33,198 --> 00:34:37,694
...have you got a department that
looks into crooked cops on the take?

357
00:34:43,709 --> 00:34:45,452
See?

358
00:34:45,794 --> 00:34:48,914
Sometimes you get pushed too hard...

359
00:34:49,173 --> 00:34:51,628
...you got a tendency to forget.

360
00:34:51,842 --> 00:34:54,000
Afternoon, Dib.

361
00:34:56,889 --> 00:34:59,806
You're not gonna let him
get away with that?

362
00:35:00,058 --> 00:35:01,221
No.

363
00:35:02,060 --> 00:35:04,053
What are you gonna do?

364
00:35:04,354 --> 00:35:06,727
I don't know...

365
00:35:06,982 --> 00:35:09,769
...but I'm gonna love it.

366
00:35:10,485 --> 00:35:12,562
Get out of town, Earp.

367
00:35:15,032 --> 00:35:18,401
- Smile when you say that, pardner.
- Oh, yeah?

368
00:35:37,346 --> 00:35:39,718
Cut! That was great.

369
00:35:41,266 --> 00:35:42,642
How'd you like it?

370
00:35:42,893 --> 00:35:44,684
It was real thrilling...

371
00:35:44,937 --> 00:35:48,187
...but I've never been
in a fight like that.

372
00:35:48,440 --> 00:35:52,105
- And Buffalo Bill didn't kill Injuns.
- You're right.

373
00:35:52,361 --> 00:35:55,445
Bill was good, but not as good
as his publicity.

374
00:35:55,656 --> 00:35:58,360
Like a movie star cowboy I know.

375
00:35:58,575 --> 00:36:04,245
I get the feeling you're not
comfortable being a famous movie star.

376
00:36:04,498 --> 00:36:10,252
What if I told you when Roosevelt
was charging up San Juan Hill...

377
00:36:10,504 --> 00:36:13,077
...I was in Muskogee busting broncs.

378
00:36:13,340 --> 00:36:16,507
I'd say that you and I
are whole lot alike.

379
00:36:16,760 --> 00:36:20,674
Part fact and just enough fiction
to sell newspapers.

380
00:36:20,931 --> 00:36:23,636
Nobody's comfortable being anything.

381
00:36:23,892 --> 00:36:29,977
I think the trick is to know the fact,
and don't believe the fiction.

382
00:36:34,278 --> 00:36:36,519
Tell me about Blackwon'th.

383
00:36:36,780 --> 00:36:40,825
Known as "Dirty Bernie."
Not a nice piece of work.

384
00:36:41,076 --> 00:36:45,489
- I think he'd like to kill one of us.
- Which one?

385
00:36:45,747 --> 00:36:46,945
Maybe both.

386
00:36:47,165 --> 00:36:51,294
If it's me, I'm counting on you
to avenge me.

387
00:36:53,672 --> 00:36:57,586
- Waterfill and Frazier?
- Oh, no. Too early.

388
00:36:57,843 --> 00:37:01,046
Says you. This morning,
I need some help.

389
00:37:02,764 --> 00:37:05,172
Do you know Rhonda Lopez?

390
00:37:05,434 --> 00:37:09,384
- The girl Michael beat up?
- Alleged to have beat up.

391
00:37:09,646 --> 00:37:13,015
Met her once or twice.
Can't say I know her.

392
00:37:13,233 --> 00:37:14,692
- Tom!
- Where's Michael?

393
00:37:14,943 --> 00:37:17,613
Gone. I tried to stop him
but he left.

394
00:37:17,863 --> 00:37:21,908
- In his underwear?
- No, in your pajamas.

395
00:37:22,534 --> 00:37:24,076
- What's that?
- Tequila.

396
00:37:24,328 --> 00:37:27,827
You know I don't drink tequila.
He called a cab.

397
00:37:28,040 --> 00:37:29,913
I tried to reach you.

398
00:37:30,125 --> 00:37:33,079
- What cab company?
- Checkered, I think.

399
00:37:33,337 --> 00:37:36,291
- Know where he went?
- No. Can you find out?

400
00:37:36,548 --> 00:37:38,707
Maybe. We gotta be careful.

401
00:37:38,967 --> 00:37:42,502
We don't want the cab company
calling the police.

402
00:37:49,853 --> 00:37:52,142
What the hell did you run into?

403
00:37:52,356 --> 00:37:55,310
Mr. Alperin wants Mr. Earp
to have lunch.

404
00:38:04,284 --> 00:38:09,112
I'm sorry we couldn't meet sooner.
I've had meetings all week.

405
00:38:09,373 --> 00:38:12,789
Twelve, sometimes 15 hours a day.

406
00:38:13,418 --> 00:38:16,206
Couldrt even have lunch till now.

407
00:38:16,421 --> 00:38:18,248
You must enjoy your work.

408
00:38:18,465 --> 00:38:21,502
Most of the time
it's a real challenge.

409
00:38:21,718 --> 00:38:25,134
Keeps me on my toes. Keeps me young.

410
00:38:25,931 --> 00:38:30,723
- Have you seen any of my pictures?
- A few.

411
00:38:35,023 --> 00:38:38,108
My biggest problem
is staying in shape.

412
00:38:41,154 --> 00:38:43,906
Not like it was when I was an acrobat.

413
00:38:44,116 --> 00:38:47,651
These days I have to steal time
just to work out.

414
00:38:47,911 --> 00:38:51,826
I've found that a strong,
agile, average man...

415
00:38:52,040 --> 00:38:56,287
...can nearly always beat a strong,
clumsy, big man.

416
00:38:56,503 --> 00:38:59,338
Now, you take, for example, Arthur.

417
00:38:59,548 --> 00:39:05,420
Remember Arthur, who was unsuccessful
in preventing you from seeing my wife.

418
00:39:05,679 --> 00:39:08,633
Please, don't misunderstand me.

419
00:39:08,891 --> 00:39:11,808
I'm not opposed to you seeing my wife.

420
00:39:12,019 --> 00:39:17,559
I'm opposed to people not doing their
jobs. It was Arthur's job to stop you.

421
00:39:17,774 --> 00:39:20,016
Even if he knew I was expected?

422
00:39:20,235 --> 00:39:22,987
But he didn't. That's the point.

423
00:39:23,197 --> 00:39:26,815
So the strong, agile, average man...

424
00:39:27,034 --> 00:39:29,607
...showed the strong, big, clumsy man.

425
00:39:29,828 --> 00:39:32,615
The error of his ways. Exactly.

426
00:39:32,831 --> 00:39:35,868
- He must love his job.
- He has no choice.

427
00:39:36,126 --> 00:39:38,961
He's on parole to me.

428
00:39:41,548 --> 00:39:47,966
There is nothing more important than
the welfare and safety of my family.

429
00:39:48,222 --> 00:39:52,136
Which brings us to the reason
that you saw my wife.

430
00:39:52,351 --> 00:39:56,479
- She asked you to help Michael.
- Did she tell you that?

431
00:39:56,688 --> 00:40:00,982
I've been told the police suspect
that he murdered Candace.

432
00:40:01,235 --> 00:40:05,232
If you really want to help,
get him to turn himself in.

433
00:40:05,489 --> 00:40:06,734
I'll try.

434
00:40:06,990 --> 00:40:08,366
Good.

435
00:40:08,992 --> 00:40:10,190
Where is he?

436
00:40:10,744 --> 00:40:12,119
Why would I know?

437
00:40:12,371 --> 00:40:16,320
You were at the Candy Store.
I presumed you helped him.

438
00:40:16,542 --> 00:40:18,748
To hide, to get away?

439
00:40:19,002 --> 00:40:23,415
If he did kill Candace Girard,
that would make me an accessory.

440
00:40:23,632 --> 00:40:26,467
I did see another
member of your family.

441
00:40:26,677 --> 00:40:31,173
Your sister Victoria
on the arm of Dutch Kieffer.

442
00:40:33,350 --> 00:40:35,141
What is it that you want?

443
00:40:35,561 --> 00:40:38,894
To do whatever I can
to help Christina.

444
00:40:39,106 --> 00:40:40,137
Why?

445
00:40:40,357 --> 00:40:43,192
Because she asked.

446
00:40:52,119 --> 00:40:54,692
That's okay, we've gotta go anyway.

447
00:40:54,955 --> 00:40:56,118
How are you?

448
00:40:56,331 --> 00:40:59,451
- Call me.
- And me too.

449
00:41:01,879 --> 00:41:03,670
I got a favour to ask you.

450
00:41:03,881 --> 00:41:07,332
I want you to tell Dirty Bernie
to lay off Wyatt.

451
00:41:07,551 --> 00:41:08,831
He won't listen.

452
00:41:09,052 --> 00:41:12,884
You don't want Earp to blow down
Alfie's house of cards.

453
00:41:13,098 --> 00:41:14,972
Expose him for what he is.

454
00:41:15,184 --> 00:41:18,303
- Just how would he do that?
- Wanna find out?

455
00:41:18,520 --> 00:41:19,896
Turn down my favour.

456
00:41:20,189 --> 00:41:23,640
Pick your ass up out of the chair.
You'll find out.

457
00:41:23,901 --> 00:41:25,359
Go ahead, Marvin.

458
00:41:25,611 --> 00:41:27,899
Take that chance.

459
00:41:28,113 --> 00:41:30,948
- I'll see what I can do.
- Not good enough.

460
00:41:31,200 --> 00:41:33,488
Either do it or don't.

461
00:41:33,744 --> 00:41:35,119
Get it?

462
00:41:38,749 --> 00:41:41,370
Have a nice day, Dib.

463
00:41:50,844 --> 00:41:52,469
How was your lunch?

464
00:41:52,679 --> 00:41:54,423
The man is crazy.

465
00:41:54,640 --> 00:42:00,180
Underneath all that happy lovability
and charm is a brutal sadist.

466
00:42:00,437 --> 00:42:03,640
- How come nobody spotted it?
- It's been spotted.

467
00:42:03,857 --> 00:42:05,897
Nobody's proven it...

468
00:42:06,109 --> 00:42:09,977
...although it's a topic of
conversation in the industry.

469
00:42:10,405 --> 00:42:12,149
I've got some bad news.

470
00:42:12,407 --> 00:42:15,278
Michael has been
arrested and booked...

471
00:42:15,536 --> 00:42:17,943
...for the murder of Candace Girard.

472
00:42:18,163 --> 00:42:21,947
They'll locate the cab driver
who picked him up.

473
00:42:22,209 --> 00:42:27,665
- Lf they tie you in, you're in danger.
- We gotta get you out of town.

474
00:42:27,923 --> 00:42:30,628
- Go to the ranch.
- And don't go home.

475
00:42:30,884 --> 00:42:33,292
Let me borrow your car.

476
00:42:36,640 --> 00:42:39,012
What's the next move?

477
00:42:39,226 --> 00:42:42,096
- What?
- He don't know how to drive.

478
00:42:54,283 --> 00:42:56,240
This time I gotta stop you.

479
00:42:56,451 --> 00:43:00,449
Tell him to go to hell.
I'll talk to the parole board.

480
00:43:00,706 --> 00:43:03,113
- They'll listen to him.
- He's worse.

481
00:43:03,333 --> 00:43:05,955
- Nothing's worse.
- I gotta see her.

482
00:43:06,211 --> 00:43:08,287
Mr. Earp, please come in.

